nodes.bodyText:
I'm still opened to use variables as column-names and other expressions, such as: CREATE STREAM .. WHERE {expression}. I had something else in mind initially when defining a char variable and replacing the variable including single- or double- quotes. That wouldn't have worked with column names. But now I completed the klip, I think we could support other places.
I still want to stay away of replacing reserved words. I noticed other systems (hive & spark) seem tp allow replacing the whole statement, like:
ksql> define select =  'select * from stream emit changes;';
ksql> {select}

I'm not sure we want to do that. It's easier to implement, but I'm not sure is correct. Most of the DBs in the market do not allow that. What do you think?

nit: I suggest making the variable value different than the variable name. Something like:







  This file contains bidirectional Unicode text that may be interpreted or compiled differently than what appears below. To review, open the file in an editor that reveals hidden Unicode characters. Learn more about bidirectional Unicode characters







        Suggested change











            ksql> DEFINE topic_prod = 'topic_prod';



            ksql> DEFINE topic_qa = 'topic_qa';



            ksql> DEFINE topic_prod = 'my_prod_topic';



            ksql> DEFINE topic_qa = 'my_qa_topic';

Will this mean that variables defined lexically after a statement that refers to them will use the latest value? As an illustration, what would be the result of following in headless mode?
DEFINE topic = 'foo';
CREATE STREAM ... WITH (kafka_topic='{topic}');
DEFINE topic = 'bar';

And regarding the SET. I didn't want to mix the current SET syntax which uses single-quotes for keynames, and I wasn't sure what other keyword to add to make reference to user-variables. Any proposal?
ksql> SET 'auto.offset.reset' = 'earliest';
ksql> SET VAR var1 = 'hola';

Yes,
ksql> set variable-substitution off;
ksql> SELECT '${foo}' as dolla_foo FROM bar;
ksql> set variable-substitution on;

I was playing with escape characters, but the \${foo} fails, and the \\${foo} results in SELECT '\${foo}'.
I wanted to be fancier and behave like Mysql and Posgtres. They do not substitute variables inside quotes. For instance:
ksql> CREATE ... WITH (kafka_topic=@topicName);
or
ksql> CREATE ... WITH (kafka_topic=:topicName);

I would have to trick the StringSubstitutor a little bit to reject replacing variables inside quotes, it's not a problem. The problem I had was how to replace this:
ksql> define colName = 'name';
ksql> SELECT id, ${colName} FROM stream;

would become:
ksql> SELECT id, "name" FROM stream;   // valid statement 
or
ksql> SELECT id, name FROM stream;     // valid statement

Hard to know.  You can do prepared statements in Mysql, but that's very hacky.
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4428761/mysql-field-name-from-variable

ksql> set variable-substitution off;
ksql> SELECT '${foo}' as dolla_foo FROM bar;
ksql> set variable-substitution on;

This seems like a reasonable limitation to me.
